\begin_layout Subsection
RNOA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
operating return
\series default
 (RNOA) is the ratio between 
\begin_inset Formula $NOPAT$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NOA$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
NFR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
net financial rate
\series default
 (NFR) is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how much the firm pays for debt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
NFR=\frac{NFE}{Avg.NFO}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When financial assets are higher than the financial obligations, the 
\begin_inset Formula $NFO$
\end_inset

 is negative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Financial Leverage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are various methods of calculating risk.
 One of them is by taking the ratio between the financing sources of a corporati
on (debt vs.
 equity).
 The more debt it has - the riskier it is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
ROE - Components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ROE can be seen as a combination of 2 components:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ROE=RNOA+FLEV\times SPREAD
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ROE=Operating\,return+Nonoperating\,return
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the spread is 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA-NFR$
\end_inset

 (the return on net operating assets, minus the financing cost).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, the values of a company are impacted mainly by its operating activities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Financial leverage can be a good thing, when the spread is positive.
 It can also go the other way round, and when the spread is negative - leverage
 decreases the ROE.
 Such companies suffer from an ROE that is worse than their 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA$
\end_inset

 (e.g Microsoft, Apple - the more they go on keeping their cash, the worse
 is their return to shareholders).
 In other words - if we separate such company to independent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

financial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 parts and invest only in the first one - we'd be better off.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Profitability Analysis - Level 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
RNOA=\frac{NOPAT}{Sales}\times\frac{Sales}{Avg.NOA}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term is the profit margin (
\begin_inset Formula $NOPM$
\end_inset

) - how much operating profit the company earns from each sales dollar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second term is the asset turnover (
\begin_inset Formula $NOAT$
\end_inset

) - the productivity of the company's net operating assets (the sales level
 realized from each dollar of assets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advantage from breaking down the 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA$
\end_inset

 to 2 components is that it allows to compare companies with similar 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA$
\end_inset

 figures, but with different strategies to make them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, consider Wal-Mart vs.
 May.
 The former one has lower profit margin, which is compenstaed by higher
 asset turnover (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cost leadership strategy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 May has a higher profit margin with a lower asset turnover (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

product differentiation strategy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generalizing, it is possible to put various industries on the asset turnover
 - profit margin graph and compare them.
 The retail/food segment operates on a very high efficiency and low profit
 margin (hard competition).
 The utilities industries are at the other extreme, with high profit margin
 and low asset turnover (they can raise the price, unless regulated).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are no industries with both high profit margin and asset turnover,
 as it would attract competitors.
 If there were industries with low profit margin and low asset turnover
 - firms would exit the business, until prices go up to another equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Leverage Illustration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 2 companies, each has $1000 financing by SSE, firm A is unleveraged
 and firm B has $1000 debt at 7%.
 In case they make both 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA=10\%$
\end_inset

, the second firm is better off (
\begin_inset Formula $NI$
\end_inset

 is 130 vs.
 100, 
\begin_inset Formula $ROE$
\end_inset

 is 13% vs 10%).
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $RNOA=2\%$
\end_inset

, the first firm is better off (having 
\begin_inset Formula $NI$
\end_inset

 20 vs.
 -30, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $ROE$
\end_inset

 is 2% vs.
 -1%).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a firm is leveraged and makes less then the interest it pays - it decreases
 its ROE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Level 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now further decompose the 
\begin_inset Formula $NOPM$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NOAT$
\end_inset

, to find out what drives the sales:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ROE=\frac{NI}{Assets}\times\frac{Assets}{Equity}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ROA=\frac{NI}{Assets};\,\,Leverage=\frac{Assets}{Equity}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ROE=\frac{NI}{Sales}\times\frac{Sales}{Assets}\times\frac{Assets}{Equity}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset Formula $ROE$
\end_inset

 equals profit margin times asset turnover times leverage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cosnder a situation when a firm borrows money in order to pay dividends
 - its ROE increases.
\end_layout

